This is a collection in prose of thirty-six love storias having a tragic ending, not intended for publication, but as material for the compositione oi his pupil.² But he was known also for his poema one of which bore the title used after him by Ovid. It has entirely perished, and we can traco only one correspondence with it, in the story of Nisus and Scylla,⁸ which was treated in the same way by Parthenius, by Ovid, and by the author of the Oisia* But this coincidence, in view oi the variatione in that story, is a striking one, and gives additional weight tc the antecedent probability that Ovid used the work largely.
